### Use Cases

You can use counter with dynamic keys, allowing you to count things that are not known at compilation time. 

For example:
```ts (wing)
let contributors = new cloud.Counter();

let github_handler = inflight (github_username: str): void => {
  let prev_contributions = contributors.inc(1, github_username);
  log("user ${github_username} has ${prev_contributions + 1} contributions");
}; 

//TODO connect github_handler to github webhook
```


### Feature Spec

As described in the [SDK Spec](https://docs.winglang.io/reference/wingsdk-spec#counter).
You can increment/decrement/peek value with `str` key, allowing you to dynamically define counters in `inflight`

- [ ] The `inc`, `dec`, `peek` functions should accept a `key: str` argument
- [ ] keys should return all keys 

```ts (wing) 
bring cloud;
let counter = new cloud.Counter();
let counter_with_initial = new cloud.Counter(initial: 100);

test "counter inc with keys" {
  assert(counter.keys().length == 0)
  assert(counter.inc(1) == 0);
  assert(counter.keys().length == 0)
  assert(counter.inc(11, "k") == 0);
  assert(counter.keys().length == 1) 
  assert(counter.inc(0, "k2") == 0);
  assert(counter.keys().length == 2) 
  assert(counter.peek() == 1);
  assert(counter.peek("k") == 11);
  assert(counter.dec(1) == 1);
  assert(counter.dec(11, "k") == 11);
  assert(counter.peek() == 0);
  assert(counter.peek("k") == 0);

  assert(counter_with_initial.inc(1) == 100);
  assert(counter_with_initial.inc(11, "k") == 100);
  assert(counter.inc(0, "k2") == 100);
  assert(counter_with_initial.peek() == 101);
  assert(counter_with_initial.peek("k") == 111);
  assert(counter_with_initial.dec(1) == 101);
  assert(counter_with_initial.dec(11, "k") == 111);
  assert(counter_with_initial.peek() == 100);
  assert(counter_with_initial.peek("k") == 100);
};
```


